{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01RvA5UTbt2H8jvK22NCiBXL","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Story created at `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/4-2-dockerfile-template-dev-integration.md`.\n\n**What was done:**\n- Discovered story 4-2 from the sprint backlog (`4-2-dockerfile-template-dev-integration: backlog`)\n- Read the epic definition (Epic 4, epics-operational-excellence.md), PRD (FR22, FR25), architecture (Decision 5), Story 4.1 (predecessor), existing templates, init orchestrator, stack detection, dev workflow patch, and infra module barrel\n- Created the story with 10 ACs, 6 task groups, and detailed dev notes\n- All 10 ACs tagged `<!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->` — every AC is testable via filesystem checks, function calls, or CLI invocation in a subprocess. None reference external workflows, sprint planning, or user sessions.\n\n## Session Issues\n\n**Problems encountered:** None.\n\n**Workarounds applied:**\n- The epic definition for Story 4.2 has only 3 ACs. I expanded to 10 to cover the implementation surface (barrel exports, Result<T> contract, InitResult extension, idempotency, compliance-by-construction). This is standard decomposition, not a deviation.\n\n**Risks identified:**\n- AC #5 (generated Dockerfile passes validateDockerfile) depends on the generated template content matching all 6 rule categories exactly. If Story 4.1's validator regex is overly strict (e.g., requiring specific apt-get patterns), the template may need careful alignment. Mitigated by testing this explicitly.\n- AC #3 (generic template) references `templates/Dockerfile.verify.generic` which currently includes `COPY . /workspace/` — this would fail the \"no source copy\" rule. The generated template for generic stacks will need to differ from the existing generic template.\n- The init orchestrator (`init-project.ts`) is already a complex file. Adding template generati