{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01DAksXvL5mX22JMUzJd3n4M","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Story 4.2: Dockerfile Template & Dev Integration\n     2→\n     3→Status: verifying\n     4→\n     5→<!-- Note: Validation is optional. Run validate-create-story for quality check before dev-story. -->\n     6→\n     7→## Story\n     8→\n     9→As a developer,\n    10→I want a Dockerfile template generated at init and a dev workflow prompt for dependency changes,\n    11→so that the Dockerfile stays correct as the project evolves.\n    12→\n    13→## Acceptance Criteria\n    14→\n    15→1. **Given** `codeharness init` detects a Node.js project (package.json exists), **When** no `Dockerfile` exists in the project root, **Then** a `Dockerfile` is generated from `templates/Dockerfile.verify` with pinned FROM, npm pack + install, verification tools (curl, jq), cache cleanup, and non-root USER. <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    16→2. **Given** `codeharness init` detects a Python project (requirements.txt or pyproject.toml exists), **When** no `Dockerfile` exists in the project root, **Then** a `Dockerfile` is generated with pinned python base, pip install, verification tools, cache cleanup, and non-root USER. <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    17→3. **Given** `codeharness init` cannot detect the project type (no package.json, requirements.txt, or pyproject.toml), **When** no `Dockerfile` exists, **Then** a generic `Dockerfile` is generated from `templates/Dockerfile.verify.generic` with basic verification tools. <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    18→4. **Given** `codeharness init` runs and a `Dockerfile` already exists in the project root, **When** init completes, **Then** the existing Dockerfile is NOT overwritten, and init logs: \"Dockerfile already exists -- skipping template generation.\" <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    19→5. **Given** a Dockerfile generated by `codeharness init`, **When** `validateDockerfile()` from Story 4.1 is run against it, **Then** it passes all 6 rule categories with zero gaps. <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    20→6. **Given** `patches/dev/enforcement.md` exists, **When** read after this story is implemented, **Then** it includes a section instructing the dev agent: \"If this story adds a new runtime dependency, check whether the Dockerfile needs updating (e.g., new system package, new binary on PATH).\" <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    21→7. **Given** the generated Dockerfile is committed to git, **When** a developer inspects it, **Then** it has comments explaining each section (base image, tools, binary install, cleanup, user) so the developer understands what to maintain. <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    22→8. **Given** `generateDockerfileTemplate(projectDir, stack)` is called, **When** it returns, **Then** it returns `Result<{ path: string; stack: string }>` following the project's Result<T> pattern. <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    23→9. **Given** `generateDockerfileTemplate()` is exported from `src/modules/infra/index.ts`, **When** imported by other modules, **Then** it is available via the barrel export only (not direct file import). <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    24→10. **Given** `codeharness init` generates a Dockerfile, **When** the init result is returned, **Then** `InitResult` includes a `dockerfile` field indicating the template was generated (e.g., `{ generated: true, stack: 'nodejs' }`). <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    25→\n    26→## Tasks / Subtasks\n    27→\n    28→- [x] Task 1: Create `src/modules/infra/dockerfile-template.ts` (AC: #1, #2, #3, #7, #8)\n    29→  - [x] 1.1: Define `DockerfileTemplateResult` interface: `{ path: string; stack: string }`\n    30→  - [x] 1.2: `generateDockerfileTemplate(projectDir: string, stack: string | null): Result<DockerfileTemplateResult>` — checks for existing Dockerfile, selects template by stack, writes to project root"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"44e99ebb-e385-42dc-a684-d204e4d10303","uuid":"174e0317-2fea-4e4b-a37f-8e957db5486a","timestamp":"2026-03-21T05:55:53.639Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/tmp/codeharness-verify-4-2-dockerfile-template-dev-integration/story.md","content":"# Story 4.2: Dockerfile Template & Dev Integration\n\nStatus: verifying\n\n<!-- Note: Validation is optional. Run validate-create-story for quality check before dev-story. -->\n\n## Story\n\nAs a developer,\nI want a Dockerfile template generated at init and a dev workflow prompt for dependency changes,\nso that the Dockerfile stays correct as the project evolves.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n1. **Given** `codeharness init` detects a Node.js project (package.json exists), **When** no `Dockerfile` exists in the project root, **Then** a `Dockerfile` is generated from `templates/Dockerfile.verify` with pinned FROM, npm pack + install, verification tools (curl, jq), cache cleanup, and non-root USER. <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n2. **Given** `codeharness init` detects a Python project (requirements.txt or pyproject.toml exists), **When** no `Dockerfile` exists in the project root, **Then** a `Dockerfile` is generated with pinned python base, pip install, verification tools, cache cleanup, and non-root USER. <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n3. **Given** `codeharness init` cannot detect the project type (no package.json, requirements.txt, or pyproject.toml), **When** no `Dockerfile` exists, **Then** a generic `Dockerfile` is generated from `templates/Dockerfile.verify.generic` with basic verification tools. <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n4. **Given** `codeharness init` runs and a `Dockerfile` already exists in the project root, **When** init completes, **Then** the existing Dockerfile is NOT overwritten, and init logs: \"Dockerfile already exists -- skipping template generation.\" <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n5. **Given** a Dockerfile generated by `codeharness init`, **When** `validateDockerfile()` from Story 4.1 is run against it, **Then** it passes all 6 rule categories with zero gaps. <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n6. **Given** `patches/dev/enforcement.md` exists, **When** read after this story is implemented, **Then** it includes a section instructing the dev agent: \"If this story adds a new runtime dependency, check whether the Dockerfile needs updating (e.g., new system package, new binary on PATH).\" <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n7. **Given** the generated Dockerfile is committed to git, **When** a developer inspects it, **Then** it has comments explaining each section (base image, tools, binary install, cleanup, user) so the developer understands what to maintain. <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n8. **Given** `generateDockerfileTemplate(projectDir, stack)` is called, **When** it returns, **Then** it returns `Result<{ path: string; stack: string }>` following the project's Result<T> pattern. <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n9. **Given** `generateDockerfileTemplate()` is exported from `src/modules/infra/index.ts`, **When** imported by other modules, **Then** it is available via the barrel export only (not direct file import). <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n10. **Given** `codeharness init` generates a Dockerfile, **When** the init result is returned, **Then** `InitResult` includes a `dockerfile` field indicating the template was generated (e.g., `{ generated: true, stack: 'nodejs' }`). <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n\n## Tasks / Subtasks\n\n- [x] Task 1: Create `src/modules/infra/dockerfile-template.ts` (AC: #1, #2, #3, #7, #8)\n  - [x] 1.1: Define `DockerfileTemplateResult` interface: `{ path: string; stack: string }`\n  - [x] 1.2: `generateDockerfileTemplate(projectDir: string, stack: string | null): Result<DockerfileTemplateResult>` — checks for existing Dockerfile, selects template by stack, writes to project root","numLines":30,"startLine":1,"totalLines":252}}}
